# Hong Kong VAR Model — Auto-Run Rules

## After any edit to the model

When `hk_var_model.py` is modified, run:

```bash
cd "/Users/stevenchung/Desktop/P12B_File/Hong Kong"
MPLCONFIGDIR=/tmp/mpl_cfg python hk_var_model.py --lag-criterion bic --model-type var
```

Use `--lag-criterion bic` as the canonical parsimonious choice. On the current 7-variable official-data snapshot, BIC selects p=1; AIC selects p=8 and is much heavier for this sample.

## After any edit to tests

When `tests/` or `hk_var_model.py` is modified, run:

```bash
cd "/Users/stevenchung/Desktop/P12B_File/Hong Kong"
MPLCONFIGDIR=/tmp/mpl_cfg python -m pytest tests/ -q --tb=short
```

All tests must pass before using the output bundle.

## After any edit to the paper

When any `.tex` or `.bib` file in `paper/` is modified, recompile:

```bash
cd "/Users/stevenchung/Desktop/P12B_File/Hong Kong/paper"
pdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex && bibtex main && pdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex && pdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex
```

## Key Project Facts

- Research question: How do US monetary policy shocks and China growth shocks propagate to HK under the currency board?
- Data: 113 quarters, 1998Q1-2026Q1, 7 variables in `data/hk_macro_quarterly_real.csv`
- Cholesky ordering: `[us_ffr, china_gdp, hk_exports_china_yoy, gdp_growth, cpi_inflation, unemployment, hibor_3m]`
- Current headline: exports-to-China and China growth explain HK real activity; US FFR mainly transmits through HIBOR and unemployment
- `MPLCONFIGDIR=/tmp/mpl_cfg` should prefix matplotlib-producing commands
